<div id="review_2948431633" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2948431633" />
    <a title="Brenda Smith" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/22325172-brenda-smith"><img alt="Brenda Smith" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1551915278p2/22325172.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2948431633?book_show_action=true">Aug 22, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Brenda Smith" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Brenda Smith" href="/user/show/22325172-brenda-smith">Brenda Smith</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2948431633" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15834824147947323696">Good Golly, I love this book! Steve McCondichie has hit a home run with Lying for A Living and its messy protagonist Jesse Few. I know this guy. He’s everywhere in the South, golfing with my dad when I was a kid and slugging ‘em back in the 19th Hole poker game. I even worked for a real estate developer just like Jesse, except that Jesse has a conscience that ultimately helps him work his way out of the many holes he’s dug for himself. There’s a sweet and subtle depth to Jesse that makes us care</span>
  <span id="freeText15834824147947323696" style="display:none">Good Golly, I love this book! Steve McCondichie has hit a home run with Lying for A Living and its messy protagonist Jesse Few. I know this guy. He’s everywhere in the South, golfing with my dad when I was a kid and slugging ‘em back in the 19th Hole poker game. I even worked for a real estate developer just like Jesse, except that Jesse has a conscience that ultimately helps him work his way out of the many holes he’s dug for himself. There’s a sweet and subtle depth to Jesse that makes us care about him a good deal and that drives us to find out how he will get out of yet another disaster. McCondichie writes refreshingly well and knows how to keep the plot moving. I've never read anything quite like Lying for A Living. It's a real treat, and I highly recommend it.</span>
  <a data-text-id="15834824147947323696" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


