<div id="review_1946299482" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1946299482" />
    <a title="Monte Dutton" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/2170604-monte-dutton"><img alt="Monte Dutton" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1442969645p2/2170604.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1946299482?book_show_action=true">Mar 19, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Monte Dutton" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Monte Dutton" href="/user/show/2170604-monte-dutton">Monte Dutton</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1946299482" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10986833292398777232">I love McCondichie&apos;s irreverent style. Lying for a Living is a broad satire on the absurdity of suburbs gone wild. Jesse Few is the corrupt epitome of the Age of Trump. He is an alpha hound with a philosophical acceptance of right being defined by that which is plausibly deniable. He overwhelms everything he touches with the contagion of his carnivorous soul.<br/>In the course of having all the rickety ethical shacks collapse at once, Jesse at least comes to feel bad about all that he has wrought by </span>
  <span id="freeText10986833292398777232" style="display:none">I love McCondichie's irreverent style. Lying for a Living is a broad satire on the absurdity of suburbs gone wild. Jesse Few is the corrupt epitome of the Age of Trump. He is an alpha hound with a philosophical acceptance of right being defined by that which is plausibly deniable. He overwhelms everything he touches with the contagion of his carnivorous soul.<br />In the course of having all the rickety ethical shacks collapse at once, Jesse at least comes to feel bad about all that he has wrought by example and demonstration. The mother of his two children has found another. Jesse blithely wrecks the relationship with a mistress. His son has been busted with the daughter of a prominent local evangelist. His financial affairs are collapsing around him, too. His mother is losing her wits. Her mystery may be the novel's most glaring loose end.<br />I'm glad the author didn't go all wholesome at the end. He leaves signs that Jesse is reaching the same maturity at the same rate as his teen-aged son JJ. For Jesse, that marks an upbeat ending.</span>
  <a data-text-id="10986833292398777232" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


